04177nam a22005535i 9780887559518DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2022361279  a97808875595187 a10.1515/97808875595182doi  a(DE-B1597)678842  a(OCoLC)1246178418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA00aGT2846.C2bB37 2021 4aGT2846.C2bB378 2022eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a391.642231 aBarbour, Dale, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUndressed Toronto :bFrom the Swimming Hole to Sunnyside, How a City Learned to Love the Beach, 1850–1935 /cDale Barbour. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tCentral Waterfront -- tCentral Waterfront -- tToronto Island -- tThe Don River and the Bathing Boy -- tHumber River Encounters -- tSunnyside and the Beach -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUndressed Toronto looks at the life of the swimming hole and considers how Toronto turned boys skinny dipping into comforting anti-modernist folk figures. By digging into the vibrant social life of these spaces, Barbour challenges narratives that pollution and industrialization in the nineteenth century destroyed the relationship between Torontonians and their rivers and waterfront. Instead, we find that these areas were co-opted and transformed into recreation spaces: often with the acceptance of indulgent city officials. While we take the beach for granted today, it was a novel form of public space in the nineteenth century and Torontonians had to decide how it would work in their city. To create a public beach, bathing needed to be transformed from the predominantly nude male privilege that it had been in the mid-nineteenth century into an activity that women and men could participate in together. That transformation required negotiating and establishing rules for how people would dress and behave when they bathed and setting aside or creating distinct environments for bathing. Undressed Toronto challenges assumptions about class, the urban environment, and the presentation of the naked body. It explores anxieties about modernity and masculinity and the weight of nostalgia in public perceptions and municipal regulation of public bathing in five Toronto environments that showcase distinct moments in the transition from vernacular bathing to the public beach: the city’s central waterfront, Toronto Island, the Don River, the Humber River, and Sunnyside Beach on Toronto’s western shoreline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBathing beacheszOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 0aBathing beacheszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy19th century. 0aBathing beacheszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aBathing customszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy19th century. 0aBathing customszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aManners and customszOntarioxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755951840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887559518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887559518/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles